## The Table From Heaven (110-115)

The story that gives this surah its name.

God reminds Jesus of all the favors given to him: speaking in the cradle, the miracles, protection from the Israelites who wanted to harm him.

Then Jesus's **disciples** (called *hawariyin* in Arabic) make a request:

> *"O Jesus, son of Mary, can your Lord send down to us a table spread from heaven?"* (112)

Jesus says: *"Fear God, if you are believers."*

They explain themselves:

> *"We wish to eat from it, and let our hearts be reassured, and know that you have been truthful to us, and be among its witnesses."* (113)

They're not asking out of disbelief. They want to eat from it, feel reassured, and be able to say: *we saw this with our own eyes*. It's similar to Abraham in Al-Baqarah asking to see the dead brought to life. Not doubt, but a desire to *witness*.

Jesus prays:

> *"O God, our Lord, send down to us a table spread from heaven to be for us a festival for the first of us and the last of us, and a sign from You."* (114)

God sends it down. But with a warning:

> *"I will send it down to you, but whoever among you disbelieves after this, I will punish them with a punishment I have not inflicted on anyone in the worlds."* (115)

You asked for a miracle. You got it. Now there's **no excuse** left. Anyone who sees this and *still* disbelieves has rejected something they witnessed firsthand.

